subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
Differs from other species of the genus by the following combination of characters. Coxa (
cx
) of male leg-pair 1 with a small lateral outgrowth (
Figs 3E, 3F
). Gonopodal promere (
pr
) relatively wide, with a long, thin, basal lamella (
la
) (
Figs 9A, 9C
). Mesomere (
ms
) rounded (
Figs 9B
, 
14C
). Lateral outgrowth (
lo
) of 
op
large, pointed distally (
Fig. 14C
). Striations on metazonae irregular, not parallel to one another (
Fig. 16C
). Ampulla 1 (
am1
) of female vulva (
vu
) not expanded, ampulla 2 (
am2
) rounded, each located at different levels; female coxa 2 (
l2
) with a small, rounded, apicomesal outgrowth (
Fig. 17C
).

Male leg-pair 1 (
Figs 3E–F
) with a well-developed suture between coxa (
cx
) and a 1-segmented telopodite remnant (
te
); 
cx
with a small lateral outgrowth, 
te
round, with a group of thick setae. Male leg-pair 2 with two coxal processes (
Fig. 4E–F
). Anterolateral process (
alp
) short and acuminate, main process (
mp
) long, straight and rod-shaped.

Promere (
pr
) relatively wide, with a lateral lamella (
la
) (
Fig. 9C
); flagella (
fl
) thickened in apical third (
Fig. 9A–B
). Mesomere (
ms
) rounded (
Fig. 9B
). Lateral outgrowth (
lo
) of opisthomere (
op
) large, pointed (
Fig. 14C
).

Ventral edge of male segment 7 with small curved lamellae bordering the gonopodal aperture (
Fig. 15C
).

Female vulva (
vu
) narrow, bursa (
bu
) with a pointed apical outgrowth. Ampulla 1 (
am1
) not expanded, ampulla 2 (
am2
) rounded, each located at different levels; coxa 2 (
l2
) with a small, rounded, apicomesal outgrowth (
Fig. 17C
, see also 
Golovatch 1981
).
